# AGENTS process (default — no reminder needed)

Treat **every** coding task that changes `api/`, `web/`, Docker, or migrations as requiring the **full** workflow in **[`AGENTS.md`](../../AGENTS.md)**. The user should **not** have to type “follow the process” — you run the deploy/verify steps yourself.

## Do by default (unless AGENTS.md says to skip)

1. **Always deploy** after changes that affect build or runtime: from the repo root run **`make dev-fast`** (preferred) or **`make dev`** — **you** execute it every time; never end with “run compose yourself” when Docker can run. Prefer **`make dev-fast`** (Postgres + **tsx** watch + **Vite**, bind mounts) for day-to-day iteration. Use **`make dev`** when you need the **same single-container image** as production (**`web/dist`** + **`api/dist`** in the **`app`** image). Skip only for **docs-only** / **comment-only** with zero ship impact.
2. **Verify** the stack: e.g. `curl` **`/api/v1/health`** → **200**, or **`docker compose ps`** (use the compose file you started).
3. **Tell the user the exact base URL**: after **`make dev-fast`**, **`http://localhost/`** when **`FAST_WEB_PORT`** is default **80**, else **`http://localhost:<FAST_WEB_PORT>/`**; after **`make dev`**, **`http://localhost/`** (port 80) or **`http://localhost:<HOST_PORT>/`**. If the classic image looks stale after **`make dev`**, run **`make dev-fresh`** and retry.
4. **`CHANGELOG.md`** — add an **`[Unreleased]`** bullet in the **same** change when behaviour or build output changes; follow **[`changelog.mdc`](changelog.mdc)** skip rules.
5. **`docs/USER_GUIDE.md`** — when operator-visible UX, routes, or labels change, update in the **same change when practical**; follow **[`user-documentation.mdc`](user-documentation.mdc)**.
6. **`git commit`** — follow **§ Git commits (commit strategy)** below and **[`git-commits.mdc`](git-commits.mdc)**. Do not leave a large uncommitted diff unless the user asked to hold commits.

## Git commits (commit strategy)

Same intent as **[`docs/DEVELOPMENT.md`](../../docs/DEVELOPMENT.md)** § *Git commits* — record work in **small, reviewable steps**, not one enormous commit at the end of a session.

**Commit after** a single coherent unit, for example:

- One feature component or vertical slice
- One bug fix (one cause / one fix)
- One refactor of a specific module or area
- Tests for one behaviour or file

If a session touches **several unrelated concerns**, use **several commits** so history stays readable and reverts stay safe.

**Message style:** short, specific, imperative — what the commit *does* (roughly ≤ 72 characters for the subject is a good habit).

| Prefer | Avoid |
|--------|--------|
| `Add set-length option to performance form` | `changes`, `fixes`, `wip` |
| `Fix bulk add range when event dates shown` | `stuff`, `updates`, `work on project` |
| `Refactor stage day time helpers` | vague one-word subjects |

**Scope with changelog and docs:** when a logical slice includes the matching **`CHANGELOG.md`** line or **`docs/USER_GUIDE.md`** tweak, put them in the **same** commit as that slice. Extended examples and edge cases: **[`git-commits.mdc`](git-commits.mdc)**. If Git is unavailable or commits fail, tell the user instead of skipping silently.

## What not to do

- Do not end a task with “you should run `make dev-fast`” / “you should run `make dev`” as the only action when you can run commands.
- Do not skip changelog because the user did not mention release notes.
- Do not assume hot reload when using **`make dev`** (compiled assets in the **`app`** image). **`make dev-fast`** does hot-reload source via bind mounts — see **[`local-docker-deploy.mdc`](local-docker-deploy.mdc)**.

